> Who among us has made a better comeback than the mighty cauliflower? Once considered uninteresting (at best), this versatile vegetable can now be spotted as a pizza crust, rice substitute, and even a hearty taco filling! Here you'll roast cumin-seasoned florets until crisp and golden. Paired with a tangy-sweet cabbage slaw, a lightly spicy curry-infused mayo, and a garnish of fresh chopped cilantro, these vegan mashup tacos are satisfying as all get-out and so loaded with bold flavors, no one will miss the meat.

Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @cauliflower florets{10%ounce} into bite-size pieces if necessary. Toss on a #baking sheet{} with a large drizzle of @cooking oil{2%teaspoon}, @cumin{1%teaspoon}, @garlic powder{1%teaspoon}, @salt{to taste}, and @pepper{to taste}. Roast on top rack until browned and tender, ~{18-20%minutes}.

Meanwhile, zest and halve @lime{1}. Roughly chop @cilantro{1/4%ounce}.

In a #large bowl{}, combine @sugar{1/2%tsp}, @salt{1/2%tsp}, and juice from the lime. Stir until sugar dissolves. Add @coleslaw mix{4%ounce} and as much lime zest as you like; toss until thoroughly combined. Refrigerate until ready to serve.

> For 4 servings, use 1 tsp sugar and 1 tsp salt for the slaw.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @vegan mayonnaise{4%tablespoon}, @curry powder{1%tsp}, and @sugar{1/4%tsp} (2 tsp curry powder and ½ tsp sugar for 4). Stir until thoroughly combined. Add @water{1%tsp} at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

> Be sure to measure the curry powder - we sent more!

Once cauliflower is done roasting, place @flour tortillas{6} on a second baking sheet and bake on top rack until lightly browned, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Divide tortillas between plates; spread with a thin layer of curry mayo. Top with roasted cauliflower and slaw. Garnish tacos with cilantro and drizzle with any remaining curry mayo. Serve.